RT @BillPascrell: Our first responders, doctors, & nurses are making heroic efforts every day, as are our neighbors staying home. But their‚Ä¶

We can do this.

We‚Äôre New Jersey.

We‚Äôre used to doing the impossible.

I cannot thank all of you who are doing the things we need you to do, in your communities, enough.

We‚Äôre working as one family should ‚Äì we‚Äôre looking out for each other and we‚Äôre supporting each other.

I just got off the phone with @realDonaldTrump ‚Äì he granted our request for access to some of the beds on the USNS Comfort.

This is a big step for us. I thank both the President and @VP.

A huge thank you to the men of @IBEW, and in particular, their state Political Director Ian Leonard, who have made a donation of much-needed PPE ‚Äì N95 masks and Tyvek gloves, jackets, and booties.

Thank you!

BREAKING: Today I‚Äôm signing an Executive Order to allow retired public employees to return to work ‚Äì in whichever capacity they can ‚Äì to help us throughout this emergency without impacting their pension status.

We need all the experienced help we can get.

Our charge to you remains the same:

Keep social distancing.

Keep washing your hands.

Keep staying indoors.

Keep being smart.

The curve is flattening.

But, this is no time to spike any footballs or to take our foot off the gas.

We still have a week-and-a-half to go, at least, until we hit the peak.

This isn‚Äôt over ‚Äì not by a long shot.

From day one, our goals have been twofold:
1Ô∏è‚É£ #FlattenTheCurve and give our health care system the ability to withstand the onslaught
2Ô∏è‚É£ Ensure that the PPE and equipment our front-line responders need gets to where it‚Äôs needed most efficiently and before there‚Äôs a crisis

This map shows us the zip codes where those of you using our self-assessment on https://t.co/JW1q8awGh7 are reporting from.

From these self-reports, we can start tracking potential hot spots and begin to assess our future equipment and PPE distribution needs. https://t.co/6LIw62y20M

We have a tough enough job as it is on the lower curve. We believe fully that we can make it given our rate of PPE acquisition. 

If you stop your social distancing, your life and the lives of our medical personnel will be in much more danger.

If we relax our social distancing, our health care system will be overrun with a surge FOUR TIMES what it could be. That would be literally disastrous.

We‚Äôre already doing all we can to uncover every piece of PPE along with every ventilator we can possibly mobilize.

If we keep up with our current practices, we can get through the peak with the hospital beds that we‚Äôre preparing.

If we relax our social distancing, we will overwhelm the system to the point that ALL of our contingency plans, and then some, will need to go into effect. https://t.co/6wgUrczC1I

If we stick to the bottom curve, we get to the peak of that flatter curve much more quickly. We can then drop down the other side that much more quickly, too.

The difference is literally in the 420,000+ positive cases we can prevent. This is not a game. This is life or death.

Look at this graph:
Shadowed line = where we would be had we done nothing
Red line = our trajectory if everyone relaxed their social distancing & stopped staying home

If we continue to stay home and practice social distancing, we can stick ourselves to the bottom curve. https://t.co/f2cbQaIrO4

In real time, we‚Äôre seeing a DECLINE in the growth rate of new cases, from 24% day-over-day on March 30th, to roughly 12% today.

Our efforts #FlattenTheCurve are STARTING TO PAY OFF. Our job now is to keep flattening it to the point where our day-over-day increase is ZERO. https://t.co/5o6MYdwYdt

We‚Äôve built a strong modeling program that we can use with great  ‚Äì and increasing ‚Äì confidence.

What we can see, together, is that while we‚Äôre not anywhere close to being out of the woods yet, we‚Äôre on the right path to get there.

When we began our preparations for responding to this emergency back in January, we knew that only an objective, fact-based, moneyball approach would get us through this. This approach has shaped our aggressive stance on social distancing.

We cannot give in to fear or sadness.

We must resolve to continue our fight together. To crack the back of this crisis. To #FlattenTheCurve. So we have fewer and fewer lives lost and friends to mourn.
